Question 1: Bias-Variance Tradeoff (25 points)

1a: Diagram

The diagram below illustrates the Bias-Variance Tradeoff. Different components of the diagram are labeled with the letters A through I. Fill in each of these labels with the name of the term or a short description.

A = Total Error

B = Variance

C = Bias ^2

D = Optimum Model Complexity

E = Error

F = Mean Squared Error

G = Bias ^2

H = Variance

I = Irreducible Error

1b. True or False: Along the dotted line (D), the value of the curve (A) is equal to the sum of curves (B) and (C).

False. The statement doesnt consider the irreducible error.

1c. True or False. The left side of the equation in Figure 1 (i.e., \(E\left[(y \hat{f}(x))^2\right]\) will never be negative.

True. It will never be negative.

1d. True or False. In general, we expect \(Var(\hat{f}(x))\) in the equation to be smaller when we use more flexible methods.

False. As we use more felxible methods, the model will fit the dataset better with low bias, and variance will be high.

1e. True or False. As we move from less flexible to more flexible methods, \([bias(\hat{f}(x))]^2\) will usually not increase.

True. With more felxible methods, model will fit the dataset better, so bias will usually not increase.

1f. True or False. More data will reduce the bias of an estimator.

True. More data generally reduces bias of an estimator as it represents more information about the true process. Mathematically, bias is a component of MSE, which is divided by n observations, and thus tends to decrease with increasing observations.

1g. True or False. More data will reduce the variance of an estimator.

True. With more data, the result would be more consistent each time we run the model, making the variance closer to the true average level, so the variance of an estimator will be reduced.

Question 2: KMEAN Clustering Problem (25 points)

We will cluster the iris dataset to understand the structure of dataset via the already designed function so-called kmeans(). We also will design a program to visually determine the number of clusters.

2a. After loading the iris dataset, retrieve the numerical measures and standardize the iris dataset. Explain how the standard deviation of variables changes.

data("iris")
# Retrieve the numerical measures and standardize
library(dplyr)
newiris <- dplyr::select_if(iris, is.numeric)
iris_s <- as.data.frame(apply(newiris, 2, function(x) (x - 
    mean(x))/sd(x)))
# Use datatable to show the change of the standard
# deviation
library("DT")
sd_original <- apply(newiris, 2, sd)
sd_scaled <- apply(iris_s, 2, sd)
colt <- cbind(sd_original, sd_scaled)
tog <- datatable(colt)
show(tog)

After standardizing, iris data has been transformed so that standard deviation equal to 1 now for all four variables

2e. Program a code to plot the scree plot (via elbow method; sum of within-cluster variance vs. k value). Determine the plausible number of clusters and explain your reasons.

set.seed(139)
# Build function to compute total within-cluster sum of
# square
wcss <- function(k) {
    kmeans(iris_s, k, nstart = 25)$tot.withinss
}

# Compute and plot wss for k = 1 to 8
k_values <- 1:8

# Extract wss for 2-7 clusters
wss_values <- map_dbl(k_values, wcss)

plot(k_values, wss_values, type = "b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
    xlab = "Number of clusters K", ylab = "Total within-clusters sum of squares")
abline(v = 3, lty = 2)

fviz_nbclust(newiris, kmeans, method = c("wss")) + geom_vline(xintercept = 3, 
    linetype = 2)

I find that 3 clusters are optimal using this method, since the location of a bend (knee) in the plot is generally considered as an indicator of the appropriate number of clusters

3c. Create various dendrograms using single, complete, and average linkage.

# Single-linkage clustering of the nutrient data
hc1 <- hclust(d, method = "single")
plot(hc1, cex = 0.6, hang = -1)

# Complete-linkage clustering of the nutrient data
hc2 <- hclust(d, method = "complete")
plot(hc2, cex = 0.6, hang = -1)

# Average-linkage clustering of the nutrient data
hc3 <- hclust(d, method = "average")
plot(hc3, cex = 0.6, hang = -1)

3d. Cut the dendrogram into groups of 5.

# Single linkage
grp1 <- cutree(hc1, k = 5)
# Complete linkage
grp2 <- cutree(hc2, k = 5)
# Average linkage
grp3 <- cutree(hc3, k = 5)

3g. Discuss the common nutrient characteristics in each group. Among three methods, Beef heart/Sardnies canned/Clams raw and clams canned are always singleton. Take average linkage clustering for example: Beef heart is high in protein and iron. Sardnies canned has much higher in calcium than the other food groups. The clam cluster(clams raw and clams canned) is low in protein and high in iron. The group (beef roast to pork simmered) are high in energy and fat compared to other groups. The largest group (mackerel to bluefish) is relatively low in iron.
